I feel like this hit a pitfall common with format screws, which is that so much focus was put on the format screw aspect that the perceived necessity of the screw took precedence over logic. I don't see a reason for this entire page to be a comic. If people reading about the characters helps them, then it makes sense to have a few panels in the addenda where people can perceive them, but having the whole thing be a comic just didn't make sense in-universe to me. I kept expecting the reason for it to be some sort of infohazard or whatever, but it was actually just  and that's just kind of flimsy. There's no reason the Foundation would let a document be this confusing and indirect when there's no info- or textual hazard at play in it. The characters recognize and cite that it's confusing for the researchers, so why hasn't a researcher formatted their article and left their panels in a different section of the article?

I upvoted at first, but the more I typed for this comment, the more I noticed the issues I have with it. I'm cool with the concept and the characters, but I don't see any compelling in-universe reasons that the format is 100% comic. So novote, but let me know if I'm missing something here and I may reconsider.





